, Graduate Engineer and Help Desk Specialist roles\n545: \n546: Show details\n547: \n548: \n549: Open to volunteer for these causes\n550: \n551: Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion, Education, Economic Empowerment, Community Improvement, Civil Rights, Social Action, and Civic Engagement, Arts and Culture, Elderly Care, Employment / Workforce Development, Environmental Sustainability, Food, Agriculture, and Nutrition, Gender Equity, Health - General and Rehabilitative, Human Rights, Medical Research, Poverty Alleviation, Mental Health and Crisis Intervention, Public Safety and Disaster Preparedness, International, Foreign Affairs, and National Security, Science and Technology, Religion\n552: \n553: Show details\n554: \n555: Suggested for you\n556: Private to you\n557: \n558: Add projects that showcase your skills\n559: \n560: Show recruiters how you put your skills to use by adding projects to your profile.\n561: \n562: Add a project\n563: \n564: Analytics\n565: Private to you\n566: \n567: 145 profile views\n568: \n569: Discover who’s viewed your profile.\n570: \n571: 108 post impressions\n572: \n573: Check out who’s engaging with your posts.\n574: \n575: Past 7 days\n576: \n577: 39 search appearances\n578: \n579: See how often you appear in search results.\n580: \n581: Show all\n582: About\n583: I help organisations and individuals solve complex technical challenges and turn them into actionable outcomes. With a background in IT operations, cloud computing, and solution consultancy, I design and implement systems that are scalable, reliable, and aligned to business goals.     \n584: \n585: \n586: \n587: I’ve led projects from end-to-end: planning, deployment, stakeholder engagement, and optimisation; ensuring technology works for people, not the other way around. I translate technical complexity into clear insights for clients, teams, and students, and I enjoy mentoring and upskilling the next generation of IT professionals.     \n588: \n589: \n590: \n591: Through roles in cloud consulting, IT support, and STEM education, I’ve developed a unique perspective that blends technical expertise with strategic thinking. I focus on creating measurable impact: improving processes, enabling digital transformation, and shaping technology adoption strategies that stick.    \n592: \n593: \n594: \n595: I’m particularly passionate about cloud solutions, system architecture, and empowering underrepresented groups in tech. I thrive at the intersection of hands-on execution and strategic guidance, building solutions and capabilities that deliver real-world results.    \n596: \n597: \n598: \n599: I do this in four different ways:  \n600: \n601: 🚀 Through intensive cloud engineering training via the AWS re/Start programme, I've gained comprehensive expertise in cloud-native application design, infrastructure automation, and security best practices. My recent implementation of containerised AI models and modern RESTful API architectures showcases my ability to architect complex cloud solutions.  \n602: \n603: 💡 Technical support and system administration for enterprise environments, including managing Azure Active Directory authentication and access control for 3,000+ staff and 20,000+ students across multiple campus locations.  \n604: \n605: 🎤 Speaking and practical instruction on #CloudComputing #SystemAdministration #VirtualizationTechnologies #ContainerizedSolutions #CloudMigration, notably through roles like STEM Ambassador and Technical Trainer at Techncamps (https://www.technocamps.com/).  \n606: \n607: You can find my work demonstrated through my First Class Dissertation on \"Levelling the Playing Field Using Generative AI Coding Assistant\", recognition as \"The Best Networker\" at USW Freelancers Academy, and ongoing contributions to the FirstGens community supporting first-generation university students in tech education.  \n608: \n609: Get in touch! andiekobbietks@outlook.com and check out my contributions at https://firstgens.co.uk/\n610: \n611: Top skills\n612: \n613: Microsoft Office • Linux • Computer Hardware • Windows\n614: \n615: Services\n616: Computer Repair\n617: \n618: Video Editing\n619: \n620: Search Engine Optimization (SEO)\n621: \n622: Web Design\n623: \n624: Data Recovery\n625: \n626: Leadership Development\n627: \n628: Backup & Recovery Systems\n629: \n630: IT Consulting\n631: \n632: WordPress Design\n633: \n634: Graphic Design\n635: \n636: Show all\n637: Featured\n638: \n639: Post\n640: \n641: From Failures and several Setbacks to First-Class & World-Class work 🙏\n642: \n643:  \n644: \n645: My own attempt at developing my own coding assistant for teaching computational thinking to school kids (Sixth formers) after using LEGO Education kits to do so for a couple of years. \n646: \n647: I turned to creating a more specialised Generative AI chatbot than ChatGPT, the culmination of my STEM Ambassadors, STEM Learning UK and Technocamps placement back at University. Pretty much my own ChatGPT alternative.\n648: \n649: This approach allowed me to create something greater than the sum of its parts. And certainly myself!\n650: \n651: I created a focused yet flexible optimised system that could effectively support learning while remaining practical and implementable with readily available tools.\n652: \n653: I wrote this thoughtful piece a long time ago and I finally get to share it, far and wide.\n654: \n655: Open to any work in that space too☺️, it always excites me!\n656: \n657: #firstgens #technology #informationtechnology #edutech #development #coding #programming #generativeai #cloudcomputing #opentowork #cloudopportunities #servicemanagement #EUC #EndUserComputing #Remote\n658: \n659: \n660: Levelling the Playing Field in Computer Science Education Using Generative Pre-trained Artificial Intelligence 🤖(aka narrow AI)\n661: \n662: Andrea 'Andie' Enning on LinkedIn • 9 min read\n663: \n664: 31 · 2 comments\n665: \n666: Post\n667: \n668: Amazon Web Services (AWS) re/Start Graduate: Empowered and Ready to Innovate! 🚀\n669: \n670: I am elated to announce that I have earned the AWS re/Start Graduate badge, a testament to my dedication and hard work in completing this comprehensive skills development program. 🎉\n671: \n672: Through Amazon re/Start, I have gained invaluable expertise in Amazon Web Services, AWS Cloud, AWS Cloud Computing, Cloud Platform, and Cloud Services. This incredibly intensive training, led by AWS professional mentors and accredited trainers, has equipped me with the technical and soft skills needed to excel in the cloud computing industry. 💻☁️\n673: \n674: As someone who believes in embodying the change I wish to see and in paying it forward, I am excited to leverage my growing expertise to drive innovation and create meaningful impact. Over the years, I’ve been privileged to support FirstGens from the ground up and inspire young learners as a STEM Learning UK Ambassador, and I look forward to continuing this journey of making a tangible difference, wherever I find myself to be!\n675: \n676: I am a natural problem-solver, always ready to tackle challenges head-on and find creative solutions. 💡\n677: \n678: Recruiters and employers, if you are seeking a passionate, skilled, and driven cloud and IT operations professional with a knack for Generative Artificial Intelligence deployment and management, I would love to connect with you. \n679: \n680: Feel free to reach out and let's start a conversation. 📩\n681: \n682: #AWSreStart #CloudComputing #TechJobs #Upskilling #InnovationDriven #FirstGens\n683: \n684: \n685: AWS re/Start Graduate was issued by Amazon Web Services Training and Certification to Andrea Enning.\n686: \n687: credly.com\n688: \n689: 37 · 21 comments\n690: \n691: Post\n692: \n693: TL;DR: A little goes a long way, find out WHY.\n694: \n695: The Colouring Book Story ✍ : Today AI is good at tasks, NOT at jobs\n696: \n697: Teachers need us, and we need them to deliver a curriculum that lives up to our times and doesn't let down another generation of humans navigating a complicated, fast-changing world. Don't let the kids beat you to it.\n698: \n699: Standing in front of a crowd can be pretty intimidating, at times, let alone kids!!!!\n700: \n701: I always recite this as a reminder of the role that each and every one of us MUST play in a society that struggles with equity, diversity, and inclusion: Pace yourself, Andie, yet know that You Were Born For a Time Like This. However the ties turn, it's about taking one brave step at a time, each and every day.\n702: \n703: Navigating the very real and impactful nature of Artificial Intelligence is feeling like every other day you could be replaced by a machine but not fearing it enough to bravely learn more about that machine, capitalise on that opportunity whilst you also realise that is as flawed as we are and therefore we need to EDUCATE, EDUCATE, EDUCATE!\n704: \n705: Our social fabric that has been gradually distorted by the attention economy, disinformation, and social media weaponisation depends on it. As Tristan Harris (founder of the Center for Humane Technology) echoed in his eye-opening documentary \"The Social Dilemma\" (a MUST Watch) and other talks over the years, which have taught me a lot. \"Harris is the closest thing Silicon Valley has to a conscience.\"-The Atlantic\n706: \n707: AI in its current form is just a tool (some argue sentient? mmh, debatable); we humans decide whether we weaponise it or make it turn us into better humans, otherwise known as augmentation.\n708: \n709: The typical double-edged sword conundrum. Superintelligence is already around the corner, as OpenAI is advancing research in that area, too, to understand the incumbent before everything starts feeling too late.\n710: \n711: This is a great initiative to work for through us, STEM Ambassadors. We are little agents of hope running around the country with our torches, lighting up the way and raising aspirations and curiosity of the future generation of Scientists, Technologists, Engineers, Artists, and Mathematicians.\n712: \n713: This time around, I delivered an interactive session on diffusion AI and text-to-image generation, discussing the ideas of creativity and imagination powered by Generative AI platforms. I couldn't have done it without the amazing resources made available for FREE by the amazing foundation that is Code.org. (Do check them out; they are doing wonders.)\n714: \n715: I taught Year 5/6 how to create their own colouring books using line art, generated images and a bit of prompt engineering (just basics, really), leading them to the realisation that the only thing that separated them from achieving such an outcome you guessed it, was their imagination.\n716: \n717: Seeing the work that Motivez does has really motivated me 😄 Keep it up, you guys! You're raising the bar high.\n718: \n719: \n720: 9 · 2 comments\n721: \n722: Link\n723: \n724: \n725: Demystifying AI: How to Use AI to Elevate Your Career in partnership with BYP Network\n726: \n727: LinkedIn\n728: \n729: Re-booted this DEI professional chapter to empower individuals to actively network cross-industries and be more aware of what is happening in the city of Cardiff, together with my phenomenal team: https://byp.network/chapters/cardiff-wales/\n730: \n731: Reshared by Andrea 'Andie' Enning\n732: \n733: Such a great memory to treasure!\n734: \n735: Thank you for contributing so much to my success by providing me with the social capital and opportunities needed to wholeheartedly serve at FirstGens!\n736: \n737: I started out as a potential First Gen to interview, immediately resonating back in 2020. I quickly became a brand ambassador, co-designer, moderator, and now a member of the Community Advisory Group—a team of movers, shakers, and legacy-makers in their own right, as I like to call them.\n738: \n739: Had I not met Alaya Holloway back when I was in uni, my story years later would have been very different! I experienced my father's loss, the pandemic, and many more hurdles.\n740: \n741: My greatest joy is to see UCAS taking onboard our directives and creating a bespoke page in collaboration with FirstGens, if you know anyone that feels a bit lost, look no further, https://lnkd.in/eyxMwsJK ! \n742: \n743: I am glad to have always held on believing in your mission and ethos, as you beautifully expressed recently, Alaya, \"Diversity is a Fact, Equity is a Choice, and Inclusion is an Action, and Belonging is an Outcome. So if we are looking to build Belonging, then we need to take Action to Include all voices so that we can achieve the outcome that we want.\"\n744: \n745: Our impact report is out now, go check it out: https://lnkd.in/eBjYqyEr\n746: \n747: —————\n748: \n749: FirstGens is a multi-award winning student platform. We support students whose parents or primary caregivers did not complete a Bachelor's degree. In doing so, we enable students to successfully navigate university.\n750: \n751: —————\n752: \n753: Through immersive community-led programmes and edtechnology, we offer comprehensive support to those who are unfamiliar with navigating higher education. In collaboration with UK universities and graduate employers, we have established an ecosystem to promote academic, personal, and professional development. \n754: \n755: Learn more at: https://lnkd.in/eTYskx-R\n756: \n757: #firstinthefamily\n758: #graduation\n759: #equalitybeyondaccess\n760: \n761: \n762: 39 · 5 comments\n763: \n764: Show all featured items\n765: \n766: Activity\n767: 1,361 followers\n768: \n769: Create a post\n770: \n771: Posts\n772: \n773: Comments\n774: View Andrea 'Andie' Enning’s profile\n775: Andrea 'Andie' Enning reposted this\n776: \n777: \n778: View company: The Algorithmic Justice League\n779: The Algorithmic Justice League\n780: \n781: 34,331 followers\n782: \n783: 22h • \n784: \n785: We know the airport feels different right now. ✈️\n786: \n787: For many in our community, including immigrants, visa holders, and travelers of color, going through security isn't just inconvenient. It can feel genuinely unsafe. And we see you. Your safety comes first. Always.\n788: \n789: For those who feel safe to do so, you still have the legal right to opt out of facial recognition at TSA checkpoints. Dr. Joy Buolamwini is here to show you how. But we want to be clear: opting out is an act of collective resistance, not an obligation. Only you can assess what's safe for you and your family.\n790: \n791: Here's what we know:\n792: 🛡️ Privacy: Your face is your most sensitive data. Once captured, we don't control how it's stored or who it's shared with.\n793: ⚠️ Security: Biometric data is subject to data breaches. Past DHS breaches show our most private information is at risk.\n794: ⚡️ Power: The rapid expansion of biometric surveillance at our borders and airports is not inevitable. We have a say.\n795: \n796: Whatever you decide at the checkpoint, knowledge is power. Catch Dr. Joy on the Science Friday podcast for a deeper dive into the harms of TSA face scans and why this fight matters now more than ever. 🎙️✨\n797: \n798: 🔗 Link to watch and learn more:\n799: https://lnkd.in/e_-idDzH… more\n800: \n801: \n802: \n803: Dr. Joy Buolamwini and 70 others reactedDr. Joy Buolamwini and 70 others\n804: \n805: 4 comments4 comments\n806: \n807: •\n808: \n809: 13 reposts13 reposts\n810: \n811: \n812: Insightful\n813: \n814: Comment\n815: \n816: Repost\n817: Send\n818: View Andrea 'Andie' Enning’s profile\n819: Andrea 'Andie' Enning reposted this\n820: \n821: \n822: View Mackenzie Jackson’s profile\n823: Mackenzie Jackson\n824: \n825:   • Following\n826: \n827: Developer and Security Advocate @ Aikido Security\n828: \n829: 1d • Edited • \n830: \n831: 👾 𝗔𝘅𝗶𝗼𝘀 𝗶𝘀 𝗮 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗷𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝘀𝗼 𝗯𝗶𝗴 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗻 𝗶𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗱𝗼𝗻'𝘁 𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝗶𝘁... \n832: 𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗱𝗲𝗳𝗶𝗻𝗶𝘁𝗲𝗹𝘆  𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝗶𝘁... 🙃 \n833: \n834: So it's important to understand what's happened and what to do. \n835: \n836: The malware is hidden in a post-install script in a dependent (plain-crypto-js)\n837: \n838: 𝘯𝘱𝘮 𝘪𝘯𝘴𝘵𝘢𝘭𝘭 → 𝘴𝘤𝘳𝘪𝘱𝘵 𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘴 → 𝘙𝘈𝘛 𝘪𝘯𝘴𝘵𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘦𝘥 𝘪𝘯 𝘴𝘦𝘤𝘰𝘯𝘥𝘴.\n839: \n840: 🔍 𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗱𝗲𝘁𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝘁𝗵𝗲𝘀𝗲 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗶𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝘀𝘆𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗺𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵 𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗴𝗿𝗲𝗽 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗮𝗻𝗱𝘀 \n841: \n842: grep -R --include=\"package-lock.json\" -E 'axios.*(1\\.14\\.1|0\\.30\\.4)|plain-crypto-js' \n843: \n844: But be careful... The script removes evidence by rewriting files like the package.json file so make sure to check installed versions and logs. \n845: \n846: 𝗬𝗼𝘂 𝘀𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗹𝗱 𝗮𝗹𝘀𝗼 𝗰𝗵𝗲𝗰𝗸 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗺𝗮𝗹𝗶𝗰𝗶𝗼𝘂𝘀 𝗯𝗶𝗻𝗮𝗿𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗼𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗺𝗮𝗰𝗵𝗶𝗻𝗲 \n847: \n848: Check for these artifacts:\n849: 𝗟𝗶𝗻𝘂𝘅 - /tmp/ld.py\n850: 𝗠𝗮𝗰𝗢𝗦 - /Library/Caches/com.apple.act.mond\n851: 𝗪𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗼𝘄𝘀 - %PROGRAMDATA%\\wt.exe\n852: \n853: If you want to prevent this kind of attack, make sure you are applying cool-down periods for new packages and use a malware firewalls which will automatically block malicious dependencies or dependencies published within a quarantine period. Checkout Aikido Safe-Chain to keep yourself protected.\n854: \n855: #cybersecurity #npm #supplychain #infosec #axios… more\n856: \n857: \n858: \n859: 123 reactions123\n860: \n861: 3 comments3 comments\n862: \n863: •\n864: \n865: 26 reposts26 reposts\n866: \n867: \n868: Like\n869: \n870: Comment\n871: \n872: Repost\n873: Send\n874: View Andrea 'Andie' Enning’s profile\n875: Andrea 'Andie' Enning reposted this\n876: \n877: \n878: View Lorna Bladen’s profile\n879: Lorna Bladen\n880: \n881:   • Following\n882: \n883: : a start-up loving marketer ~ SMB community manager at Canva | Interests in growth marketing + community building\n884: \n885: 6d • \n886: \n887: Calling all graphic designers and creators across the UK 🇬🇧 \n888: \n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-888. Use offset=889 to continue.)\n</content>",
